\f0\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ARC-AGI Project: Milestone D\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf4 \cb1 First, make sure to read the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://gatech.instructure.com/courses/498210/pages/arc-agi-project-overview"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 full project overview}}. It contains instructions for the project as a whole and getting started with the code. This page describes only what you should do for Milestone D within the broader context of that project overview.\
For Milestone D, your goal is to simply demonstrate that you have made some progress in creating an agent that can address the Set D problems of our ARC-AGI test, especially the Training D and Test D problems. 50% of your grade on Milestone D is earned by meeting the minimum performance requirements; 50% of your grade is earned by completing the milestone journal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Performance Requirement\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf4 \cb1 50% of your Milestone grade comes from your agent's performance on the Set D problems: 25% from the Training D problems, and 25% from the Test D problems. To earn the full 25% on each set, you must answer at least 6 problems in that set. Answering more than 6 problems does not grant any extra credit, but it does get you ahead for the Final ARC-AGI project, where you'll submit one final agent that runs against all 96 ARC-AGI problems.\
Answering fewer than 6 questions will earn the equivalent fraction of the 25% (e.g. 20.8 points for answering 5/6, 16.7 for 4/6, 12.5 for 3/6, etc.).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 Performance Submission Instructions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf4 To fulfill the Performance Requirement, follow the directions on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://gatech.instructure.com/courses/498210/pages/arc-agi-project-overview"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 full project overview}}\'a0for submitting to Gradescope, and then submit your agent to the Milestone D assignment.\
After submitting to the Milestone D assignment in Gradescope, make sure to select which submission you want to have count for your graded submission. By default, Gradescope will use your latest submission, but you may want to use an earlier one. After the deadline, this will be exported to Canvas to calculate your final Milestone grade.\
You may submit up to 40 times prior to the deadline. The large majority of students do not need nearly that many submissions, so do not feel like you should use all 40; this cap is in place primarily to prevent brute force methods for farming information about patterns in hidden test cases or submitting highly random agents hoping for a lucky submission. Note that Gradescope has no way for us to increase your individual number of submissions, so we cannot return submissions to you in the case of errors or other issues, but you should have more than enough submissions to handle errors if they arise.\
This is an individual assignment.\'a0All work you submit should be your own. Make sure to cite any sources you reference or code you use (in accordance with the broader class policy on code reuse).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Milestone Journal\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf4 \cb1 In addition to submitting an agent to Gradescope, you will also submit a brief milestone journal to the Milestone D assignment in Canvas. Your Milestone Journal must be written in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://gatech.instructure.com/courses/498210/files/folder/Journal%20Templates#"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 JDF format}}. There is no maximum length; we expect most submissions to be around 5 pages, but you may write more if you would like. Writing the journal is intended to be a useful exercise for you first and foremost: it should let you externalize and formalize your ideas, it should let you get feedback from your classmates, and it should let your classmates learn from you. Your journal should not include actual code; it should just include a description of your agent\'92s approach.\
Note that your Milestone D should be all original content; if there is content that you wrote for a previous Milestone that is still pertinent, you may refer back to that content again (including quoting yourself), and then go on to discuss what has changed or what is new (or, why the same content you wrote previously is still so applicable).\
If you need to quote large portions of your prior writing, you can use a blockquote, or include your prior Milestone in an appendix that you refer to. The important element is for TAs and classmates to be able to identify the new content.\
For Milestone D, you should answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How does your agent currently function? Depending on the inner workings of your agent, there may be a lot of different ways to describe this. For example, does it select from multiple problem-solving approaches depending on what it sees in the problem? Does it perform shape recognition or direct pixel comparison? Does it generate multiple variations of one solution approach, or does it generate a separate solution for each of multiple approaches? You need not answer these specific questions, but they are examples of ways you might describe your agent\'92s design.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How well does your agent currently perform? How many problems does it get right on the Set D problems?\'a0\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
What problems does your agent perform well on? What problems (if any) does it struggle on? Why do you think it performs well on some but struggles on others (if any)?\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How efficient is your agent? Does it take a long time to run (give specific metrics)? Does it slow down significantly on certain kinds of problems? If so, by how much? Why do you think your agent runs slower on certain problems?\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How do you plan to improve your agent\'92s performance on these problems before the final project submission?\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
What feedback would you hope to get from classmates about how your agent could do better? What are some of the challenges you are facing (or think you will face later) that could benefit from someone else\'92s feedback?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

